          "body": "Buried in the movement of praise and preceding the return to crisis, verse 11 contains the psalm's most theologically searching request: 'Unite my heart to fear Your name.' The Hebrew *yachad levav* means to make the heart one, to bring the scattered allegiances of the inner person into a single orientation. David does not ask primarily for the defeat of his enemies, for long life, or even for peace — he asks for a heart that is not divided. The request implies an honest self-diagnosis: without God's unifying work, the heart will be pulled toward lesser fears, lesser loves, lesser gods. Howard Hendricks frequently pressed students on what they most urgently needed in their walk with God — this verse shows David's answer: not better circumstances but better integration. The undivided heart does not fear the enemy of verse 14 because it is fully occupied fearing the God of verse 15. John Owen, in his treatment of spiritual-mindedness, argued that the chief remedy for a wandering, double-minded soul is precisely this: an increase of the fear of God that crowds out all competing anxieties. Verse 11 asks for that remedy by name."
