          "body": "Verse 15 is one of the most significant single verses in Psalm 86: 'But You, O Lord, are a God merciful and gracious, slow to anger and abundant in lovingkindness and truth.' This is a direct quotation of Exodus 34:6 — the moment when God revealed His name to Moses after the golden calf catastrophe, granting the deepest self-disclosure in the Torah. The same formula is quoted or echoed in Numbers 14:18, Nehemiah 9:17, Psalms 103:8, 145:8, Jonah 4:2, Joel 2:13, and Nahum 1:3. It became the foundational creed of Israel's covenant theology. David's act of citing it here is pastorally precise: the worst threat against his life (v.14) is met not by mustering his own resources but by returning to the definitive moment of divine self-revelation. The argument is: You told Moses who You are. I am appealing to that same character now. This is covenant prayer at its most rigorous — the worshipper arguing from revelation, not from feeling."
