        "body": "The psalm opens with a rapid-fire sequence of imperatives: 'Incline... answer... preserve... save... be gracious... make glad... give ear... give heed' — eight commands in seven verses directed to God. This is not irreverence. In the ancient Near Eastern context, the *eved* (servant/slave) who belonged to a great household had an established right to petition his master, precisely because the relationship was binding on both parties. David is not demanding but claiming — pressing his legitimate access.\n\nThe arguments David deploys in verses 1-5 are carefully layered. First, his condition: 'I am afflicted and needy' (v.1). The Hebrew terms *ani* (poor, afflicted) and *evyon* (needy, destitute) together paint the most vulnerable possible self-portrait. But notably, the needy person in the Psalter is consistently the recipient of divine attention — Psalm 72:12-13; Isaiah 25:4. Poverty before God is a qualification for divine care, not a disqualification.\n\nSecond, his identity: 'I am a godly man' (*chasid*, v.2). This is not self-righteousness — *chasid* denotes the recipient of God's *chesed*, one who is bound to God in covenant loyalty. David claims the same covenant bond that grounds his petition. Third, and most powerfully, God's own character: 'For You, Lord, are good, and ready to forgive, and abundant in lovingkindness to all who call upon You' (v.5). The 'for' (*ki*) clause shifts the argument entirely from David's merit to God's nature. Peter Davids, commenting on the parallel logic in James 1:5, notes that the character of the Giver — not the worthiness of the asker — is the theological ground of confident prayer.\n\nVerse 7 closes the movement with a confidence-declaration: 'In the day of my trouble I shall call upon You, for You will answer me.' The certainty of 'You will answer' is grounded not in past experience alone (though v.13 adds that dimension) but in the character declared in v.5. David's confidence is theological before it is experiential.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chasid* (v.2) shares the root with *chesed* — David is the covenant-bound one appealing to the covenant-loyal God. *Sallach* (ready to forgive, v.5) appears in the Hebrew Bible almost exclusively with God as subject — it is a word that belongs uniquely to divine action, not human. *Evyon* (needy, v.1) is used in the Psalter for the poor who are the special object of divine protection (Ps 72:4, 12; 82:4; 113:7)."
