        "body": "The shift from petition to doxology at verse 8 is abrupt by Western rhetorical standards but entirely natural in Hebrew prayer. The psalmist who has been arguing for God's attention suddenly turns to declaring God's identity — not to escape the crisis but to situate it within a larger reality. This pattern is common in Psalms (cf. Psalms 22:3-5; 40:1-3) and reflects the conviction that sustained prayer must think hard about the One being addressed.\n\nThe incomparability formula of verse 8 — 'There is no one like You among the gods' — has deep roots in the Exodus tradition. Exodus 15:11 uses the identical Hebrew construction (*mî kamôka ba-elim*) after Israel crossed the sea: 'Who is like You among the gods, O Lord?' The formula was Israel's creedal response to the great act of divine power. David reaches for it in a personal crisis, implicitly claiming: what You did at the Exodus is the measure of what You can do here. The gods of the nations have neither character (v.5) nor works (v.8) nor uniqueness (v.10) to match Yahweh.\n\nVerse 9 then makes an extraordinary move: 'All nations whom You have made shall come and worship before You, O Lord, and they shall glorify Your name.' This is not political optimism but eschatological faith. The nations are already in view in the Psalter's theology — Psalm 2:8; 22:27-28; 47:9; 72:11 all envision universal worship of Yahweh. David is praying from inside a specific crisis but thinking from inside the largest possible theological framework. The man who cannot guarantee his life will survive the week (v.14) is confident that the nations will bow to his God at the end of history. This is precisely the kind of perspective that Spurgeon, preaching on this psalm, called 'the missionary motive embedded in personal extremity.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pala* (wondrous deeds, v.10) — the same root for the 'wonders' of Exodus (Exod 15:11); its use here is a deliberate Exodus echo. *Bad* (alone, v.10) — the strongest Hebrew term for exclusivity; 'You alone are God' is the Old Testament's clearest statement of exclusive monotheism in the Psalter."
