        "body": "Verses 11-13 form the psalm's theological center of gravity. David moves from doxology (vv.8-10) into an act of personal consecration that is simultaneously a petition, a vow, and a confession of need. The triad of verse 11 is structurally tight: 'Teach me Your way' (a request for instruction), 'I will walk in Your truth' (a responsive vow of obedience), 'unite my heart to fear Your name' (a request for the inner transformation that makes the obedience possible).\n\nThe final clause of verse 11 — *yachad levav-i le-yir'ah shem-ekha*, 'unite my heart to fear Your name' — is among the most psychologically honest requests in the Psalter. *Yachad* means to make one, to bring into unity what has been scattered. David is confessing that his heart is, in its natural state, divided — pulled toward multiple objects of trust and fear. The remedy he seeks is not willpower or self-discipline but a divine unifying act. John Owen, in *Pneumatologia*, argued that only the Spirit of God can integrate the human will around the fear of God; verse 11 embodies that pneumatological insight as a prayer. This is not simply a call for greater devotion; it is a recognition that the wholeness of heart required for genuine fear of God is a gift, not an achievement.\n\nVerse 12 then shows what the undivided heart does: it praises with *all* the heart (*bekol-levav*) and glorifies God's name *forever* (*le-olam*). The total-heart praise and the perpetual vow are the expressions of the integration requested in verse 11. And verse 13 grounds both in history: 'For Your lovingkindness toward me is great, and You have delivered my soul from the depths of Sheol.' The praise is not generic; it has a specific memorial event. The word *natsal* (delivered) describes a snatching-from-danger — used frequently of God's rescue in critical moments (Exodus 3:8; Psalm 18:17; 33:19). David has been at the edge of death before and been pulled back. That history funds the present confidence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yachad* (unite, v.11) appears elsewhere in the Psalter at Psalm 133:1 — 'how good and pleasant it is for brethren to dwell together in unity.' The same unifying that blesses community David requests for his inner life. *Sheol tachti* (depths of Sheol, v.13) — the superlative of the underworld, the furthest point of mortal danger. *Natsal* (delivered) is often a rescue from an aggressor, not merely from impersonal fate."
