        "body": "Having moved through petition (vv.1-7), doxology (vv.8-10), and consecration (vv.11-13), David now names the crisis with full specificity. 'Arrogant men' (*zedim*, insolent, presumptuous ones) and 'a band of violent men' (*edah aritsim*, an assembly of ruthless/tyrants) 'have sought my life' — *nephesh* again, the whole person, the target of the assault. The defining characteristic of these enemies is given in the final clause of verse 14: 'they have not set You before them.' They are not merely David's enemies; they are God's enemies by choice. The arrogant of the Psalter are consistently those who operate as if God is absent or irrelevant (cf. Psalm 10:4; 14:1; 36:1).\n\nThen comes the psalm's most powerful rhetorical move — the *we-attah* ('but You') adversative pivot of verse 15. Against the character of the arrogant enemies, David sets the character of God. And the character he recites is not a general theological claim but the specific Exodus 34:6 formula: 'merciful and gracious (*rachum we-channun*), slow to anger (*erekh appayim*), and abounding in lovingkindness and truth (*rav-chesed we-emet*).' This is the most quoted single verse in the Hebrew Bible — cited across eight subsequent books (Numbers, Nehemiah, Psalms, Joel, Jonah, Micah, Nahum, and here). Each citation uses it to anchor a present crisis in the definitive self-revelation God gave to Moses.\n\nThe theological logic is precise. The context of Exodus 34 is catastrophic covenant breach — Israel had worshipped the golden calf. God's revelation of His name came *after* the worst possible act of infidelity, not before it. David knows this context and is invoking it: the same God who disclosed His character to a people who had catastrophically failed is the same God being petitioned now. Tim Keller, in his treatment of Psalm 86 in *The Songs of Jesus*, observes that the crisis of verse 14 is not answered by the defeat of the enemies in verse 17 alone — it is first answered by the recitation of verse 15. Theology precedes deliverance; the character of God is the first and deepest comfort.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Zed* (arrogant, v.14) — from a root meaning to boil up, to seethe; the insolent one who has puffed himself up against both God and man. *Rachum we-channun* (merciful and gracious, v.15) — *rachum* derives from *rechem*, womb; a compassion as instinctive and deep as a mother's love for the child she has carried. *Erekh appayim* (slow to anger) — literally 'long of nose/nostril,' since anger in Hebrew idiom was imagined as flared nostrils; long-nosed = slow to reach the point of anger."
