        "body": "The psalm closes with a cluster of petitions that draw together the threads of the whole poem. 'Turn to me' (*panah*) — the request that God redirect His face from elsewhere to this specific servant in this specific crisis. The same word is used when a king turns his attention toward a petitioner; the image is of divine regard, the face of favor rather than the averted gaze of judgment (cf. Numbers 6:25-26). 'Be gracious to me' (*chanan*) — already prayed in verse 3, now repeated at the crisis's sharpest moment; the request for grace presupposes unworthiness, not merit.\n\nThe identity-claim of verse 16 — 'save the son of Your handmaid' (*ben-amatekha*) — is an intensification of the servant-language throughout the psalm. The son of a *amah* (female slave/maidservant) was born into the household; his belonging was not earned but inherited. David's appeal is hereditary as well as relational: he is not merely a servant by contract but a servant by birth, one whose place in God's household is part of his origin. The same formula appears in Psalm 116:16, also a psalm of deliverance from death's edge.\n\nThe request for 'a sign for good' (v.17) is the psalm's most culturally specific petition. David asks not merely for private assurance but for a visible, public token of divine favor — so that 'those who hate me may see it and be ashamed.' The sign is not for David's personal comfort alone; it is apologetic, even evangelistic in scope. The enemies who 'have not set You before them' (v.14) would, by the sign's visibility, be confronted with the God they ignored. This connects the personal crisis to the universal vision of verse 9 — the nations bowing before Yahweh. Even in his own deliverance, David hopes for the further reach of divine glory.\n\nThe psalm's final word is *nacham* — 'comforted me.' David speaks of God's comfort in the perfect tense, as though already received. The prayer ends not in ongoing petition but in settled assurance. The transition from 'afflicted and needy' (v.1) to 'helped and comforted' (v.17) is the psalm's whole arc, and the movement is made not by a change of external circumstances but by the sustained apprehension of who God is — the God of Exodus 34, the maker of all nations, the one who unites the divided heart, the one who delivers from the depths of Sheol.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Oz* (strength, v.16) — power, might, but frequently in the Psalter the kind of strength God imparts to the weak rather than power the strong already possess (Ps 29:11; 46:1; 68:35). *Nacham* (comforted, v.17) — from the same root as Nahum and the comforter-language of Isaiah 40:1 ('comfort, comfort My people'); a deep settling of distress, not surface reassurance."
